# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Broke the problem down into steps:

1. Iterate through each bit of the number
2. Count the number of zeroes between each pair of ones
3. return the greatest 'gap'.

---
The following code iterates through the each bit from right to left:
```
while(n != 0){
    int a = n & 1; // retrieves the rightmost bit.
    n >>= 1; // performs a logical bitewise shift right.
}
```
This boolean variable ensures that the counter "runningCount" does not begin counting the zeroes until the first "1" is encountered:
```
boolean first = true;
```
When a second "1" bit is encountered, a check is made to see if the "runningCount" is greater than the recorded "max" count and "max" is updated accordingly.

---

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int binaryGap(int n) {

        int max = 0;
        int runningCount = 0;
        boolean first = true;

        if(Integer.bitCount(n) == 1){
            return 0;
        }

        while(n != 0){
            int a = n & 1;
            n>>=1;
            if(a == 1){
                if(runningCount > max){
                    max = runningCount;
                }
                runningCount = 1;
                first = false;
            }
            else if(first == false){
                runningCount++; 
            }
        }
        return max;
    }
}
```

