**Please upvote if you like the solution, it motivates me to post more of them**

**Solution 1: 10 4bit counters packet into a 64bit integer**

This solution is basically do a frequency count. Since any digit (0 to 9) is for sure less frequent than 16 in a 32bit integer we can use 4 bits to count the frequency the digitis. With that we can pack 10 4bit counters easily into a 64bit integer. The solution has to functions:

We just need to compare the signature of ```n``` with the signature of all powers of 2.

```
    bool reorderedPowerOf2(int n) {
        const uint64_t sig_n = signatur(n);
        // Compare to all powers of 2.
        for (int i = 0; i < 32; ++i) {
            if (sig_n == signatur(1 << i)) return true;
        }
        return false;
    }
```

The more interesting part is to compute the singatures:

```
    // We use 4 bits to count each digit.
    static uint64_t signatur(uint32_t n) {
        uint64_t sig = 0;
        while (n) {
            sig += 1UL << ((n % 10) * 4);
            n /= 10;
        }
        return sig;
    }
```

Alternative to an ```uint64_t``` signature we could have used an ```array<char, 10>``` (or a similar structure) or just use a ```string``` and just sort the digits.

As always feedback is welcome.

