My first thought was going towards generating all posibilities of orders of N's numbers and check if it's a pow by math.
Then I was thinking, we only have to check even numbers

But then I took a look at all the numbers that are  power of 2 under 10^9
There are only 29 numbers there, as 2^30 is already over 10^9: 1,073,741,824

So if we generate those pows, or at least up to the N.length + 1
We can then check the numbers that have the same length by a frequency map
If the frequency map of N and one of the target powers is the same, we have a match.

For example: 1234
All the powers of 2 of length 4 (it always has to be the same length as N of course) are:
[ 1024, 2048, 4096, 8192 ]

The frequency map of 1234 is:
{ '1': 1, '2': 1, '3': 1, '4': 1 };

Versus one of the powers of 2:
{ '1': 1, '0': 1, '2': 1, '4': 1 };
	will not match.

But if we had 1204 as N then we have a freq map of: { '1': 1, '2': 1, '0': 1, '4': 1 };
Though not in the same order as the freq map of 1024, a simple for loop will match them.

